Retail and Geodemographics: A Spatial Data Science Approach

Patrick Ballantyne

2022-09-23

1 Libraries

Libraries are an essential part of the R workflow, giving you all the necessary tools to complete the analysis. Different people use different libraries for certain aspects of analysis, but these are my favourites:

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(tidycensus)
library(tmap)

1.1 Store data - SafeGraph places

places <- st_read("Data/places.gpkg", quiet = TRUE)

Look at the attributes:

glimpse(places)

Lets take a look at the distribution of grocery stores:

grocery <- places %>%
  filter(top_category == "Grocery Stores")
tm_shape(grocery) +
  tm_dots(col = "brands", size = 0.05) +

Lots of Independent grocery stores, but also large numbers of big brands such as LIDL, Circle K and Whole Foods.

The TractGroup column is the one we are interested in; every census tract in the US is assigned to one of 10 groups, based on the geodemographic characteristics of the area in question.

tm_shape(geodemo) +
  tm_fill(col = "TractGroup", alpha = 0.5) +
  tm_borders(col = "black", lwd = 0.25) +
  tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE)

2 Store Catchments

Ok, now that we are familiar with the three main datasets, we can actually get to some spatial data science. In this workshop we are going to be looking at the geodemographic profiles of two very different retailers:

Whole Foods Market:

The stores offer a wide variety of organic and natural foods, as well as a large selection of prepared foods also has a number of unique features, such as a cheese shop, a wine bar and a coffee bar. Shopping at this luxury grocery store might cost shoppers more than they are willing to spend. According to a survey conducted by Business Insider, Whole Foods is 15% more expensive than general grocery stores such as Walmart and Kroger (source: gobankingrates.com).

Ollies Bargain Outlet:

Ollies Bargain Outlet is an American chain of discount closeout retailers Its selection of merchandise comprises a variety of discounted household goods, apparel, pet supplies, kitchen pantry staples, and seasonal products (holiday, gardening, patio, pool and beach supplies); a majority of these items are unsold or overstocked merchandise that is purchased in bulk from other retailers and sold at discounted prices (source: wiki).

Lets get the relevant places:

wholefoods <- places %>%
  filter(brands == "Whole Foods Market")

ollies <- places %>%
  filter(brands == "Ollie's Bargain Outlet")

Lets visualise these:

q1 <- tm_shape(wholefoods) +
  tm_dots(col = "black", size = 0.1) +
  tm_text("brands", size = 0.5) +
  tm_shape(ollies) +
  tm_dots(col = "black", size = 0.1) +
  tm_text("brands", size = 0.5)

q1

And what does this look like with the geodemographic classification underneath:

tm_shape(gd_pop) +
  tm_fill(col = "TractGroup", alpha = 0.5) +
  tm_borders(col = "black", lwd = 0.1) +
  tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE) +
  q1
## Some legend labels were too wide. These labels have been resized to 0.63, 0.62. Increase legend.width (argument of tm_layout) to make the legend wider and therefore the labels larger.

So there are some pretty obvious locational differences between them. But how can we assess this - catchments. Store catchments help us to better understand the characteristics of consumers that are likely to use these stores.

Lets build a 1km buffer for whole foods stores:

wholefoods_catch <- st_buffer(wholefoods, 1000)

What do these look like:

q2 <- tm_shape(wholefoods) +
  tm_dots(col = "black", size = 0.1) +
  tm_text("brands", size = 0.5) + 
  tm_shape(wholefoods_catch) +
  tm_polygons(col = "red", alpha = 0.3)
q2

And with the geodemographic:

tm_shape(gd_pop) +
  tm_fill(col = "TractGroup", alpha = 0.5) +
  tm_borders(col = "black", lwd = 0.1) +
  tm_layout(legend.outside = TRUE) +
  q2
## Some legend labels were too wide. These labels have been resized to 0.63, 0.62. Increase legend.width (argument of tm_layout) to make the legend wider and therefore the labels larger.

Lets repeat the same for Ollies Bargain Outlet

ollies_catch <- st_buffer(ollies, 1000)

What do these look like:

q3 <- tm_shape(ollies) +
  tm_dots(col = "black", size = 0.1, alpha = 0.3) +
  tm_text("brands", size = 0.8) + 
  tm_shape(ollies_catch) +
  tm_polygons(col = "red", alpha = 0.3)
q3

And with the geodemographic:

tm_shape(gd_pop) +
  tm_fill(col = "TractGroup", alpha = 0.5) +
  tm_borders(col = "black", lwd = 0.1) +
  tm_layout(legend.outside = T) +
  q3
## Some legend labels were too wide. These labels have been resized to 0.63, 0.62. Increase legend.width (argument of tm_layout) to make the legend wider and therefore the labels larger.

So there are some obvious differences between the general location and geodemographic profile of Whole Foods vs Ollies Bargain Outlet. So, how do we quantify this: catchment profiling.

3 Catchment Profiling

Catchment profiling is not a new approach, with retailers commonly using it to better understand the characteristics of people living in the catchments of their stores. However, what we want to introduce you to is a method through which to make this much simpler, accounting for a vast array of characteristics all at once: catchment geodemographic profiling.

3.1 Catchment Geodemographics (Whole Foods Market)

Ok, so we have already constructed catchment for each of these stores, enabling us to identify people living nearby that are more likely to shop there, we can profile exactly who these people are.

Lets do a spatial join, allowing us to see what tracts (and geodemographics) fall within each store catchment:

wholefoods_gd <- st_join(wholefoods_catch, gd_pop)

Lets take a look at the output:

What we want to do for each store is calculate the total catchment population in the catchment, and the total population disaggregated by geodemographic group. This is easy with tidyverse.

First, get the total population in each catchment:

wholefood_profile <- wholefoods_gd %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-c(geom)) %>%
  group_by(location_name, placekey) %>%
  summarise(catch_pop = sum(value))

Then get the total population by geodemographic group in each catchment:

wholefood_gd_profile <- wholefoods_gd %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-c(geom)) %>%
  group_by(location_name, placekey, TractGroup) %>%
  summarise(catch_gd_pop = sum(value))

Bring the two values together:

wholefood_profile <- merge(wholefood_profile, wholefood_gd_profile, by = c("location_name", "placekey"), all.x = TRUE)
head(wholefood_profile)
##        location_name            placekey catch_pop                  TractGroup
## 1 Whole Foods Market 222-224@8g6-y44-435     23815 B: Wealthy Nuclear Families
## 2 Whole Foods Market 222-224@8g6-y44-435     23815   F: Low Income and Diverse
## 3 Whole Foods Market zzw-222@8g6-ycc-3wk     32449 B: Wealthy Nuclear Families
## 4 Whole Foods Market zzw-222@8g6-ycc-3wk     32449   F: Low Income and Diverse
## 5 Whole Foods Market zzw-222@8g6-ykz-9vf     14710 B: Wealthy Nuclear Families
## 6 Whole Foods Market zzw-222@8g6-ykz-9vf     14710        E: Wealthy Urbanites
##   catch_gd_pop
## 1        19238
## 2         4577
## 3        22361
## 4        10088
## 5         4015
## 6         6826

Calculate proportion of catchment occupied by each geodemographic group:

wholefood_profile_final <- wholefood_profile %>%
  mutate(gd_prop = (catch_gd_pop / catch_pop) * 100) %>%
  select(location_name, placekey, TractGroup, gd_prop)

Lets visualise the breakdown of different groups between stores:

wholefood_profile_final %>%
  complete(TractGroup, location_name, placekey, fill=list(gd_prop=0)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = TractGroup, x = placekey, y = gd_prop)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())

3.2 Catchment Geodemographics (Ollies Bargain Outlet)

Lets repeat those steps for Ollies Bargain Outlet:

ollies_gd <- st_join(ollies_catch, gd_pop)
ollies_profile <- ollies_gd %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-c(geom)) %>%
  group_by(location_name, placekey) %>%
  summarise(catch_pop = sum(value))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'location_name'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ollies_gd_profile <- ollies_gd %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-c(geom)) %>%
  group_by(location_name, placekey, TractGroup) %>%
  summarise(catch_gd_pop = sum(value))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'location_name', 'placekey'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
ollies_profile <- merge(ollies_profile, ollies_gd_profile, by = c("location_name", "placekey"), all.x = TRUE)
ollies_profile_final <- ollies_profile %>%
  mutate(gd_prop = (catch_gd_pop / catch_pop) * 100) %>%
  select(location_name, placekey, TractGroup, gd_prop)

And visualise the output:

ollies_profile_final %>%
  complete(TractGroup, location_name, placekey, fill=list(gd_prop=0)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = TractGroup, x = placekey, y = gd_prop)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())

3.3 Catchment spending power

Whilst it is useful to visualise differences in geodemographic profiles of store catchments, it is perhaps more useful to provide an empirical measure that quantifies these differences.

Based on the methodology applied in Singleton et al.(2016), we calculate a Insert snazzy name score for each store catchment, which is based on differences in income between the different groups.

Lets read in a file containing some information about the overall wealth of these different groups. For each geodemographic group, we have prepared a summary of the overall wealth taken straight from the pen portrait in Spielman and Singleton (2015). Using these descriptions, we have assigned an arbitrary z-score (or weight) which can be used to weight these population proportions, and derive a composite index from them.

zscores <- read.csv("Data/z-scores.csv")
zscores
##                                  TractGroup
## 1                      A: Hispanic and Kids
## 2               B: Wealthy Nuclear Families
## 3     C: Middle Income, Single Family Homes
## 4                      E: Wealthy Urbanites
## 5                 F: Low Income and Diverse
## 6                     G: Old, Wealthy White
## 7               H: Low Income, Minority Mix
## 8             I: African American Adversity
## 9 J: Residential Institutions, Young People
##                                                  Wealth z.score
## 1                     Low incomes and public assistance    0.25
## 2           High incomes, few households less than $50k    1.00
## 3     Retirement income, low to middle household income    0.50
## 4          Wealthy, many households over $200k per year    1.00
## 5  Incomes below $40k common, few households over $100k    0.25
## 6             Retirement income, many households $150k+    0.50
## 7                     Low incomes and public assistance    0.25
## 8 Very poor, public assistance, incomes over $100k rare    0.05
## 9                                            Low income    0.25

Merge the z-scores onto the profiles:

wholefood_profile_final <- merge(wholefood_profile_final, zscores[, c("TractGroup", "z.score")], all.x = TRUE)

Weight the geodemographic population proportions with the z scores:

wholefood_profile_final <- wholefood_profile_final %>%
  arrange(location_name, placekey) %>%
  mutate(w_gd_prop = gd_prop * z.score)

Take a look:

head(wholefood_profile_final)

Finally, we want to calculate an aggregate score, which uses these weighted catchment proportions to derive a score that represents the insert snazzy name of the stores catchment.

wholefood_out <- wholefood_profile_final %>%
  select(location_name, placekey, w_gd_prop) %>%
  group_by(location_name, placekey) %>%
  summarise(exp = sum(w_gd_prop))

## `.groups` argument.

Ok, lets compare the distribution of our score across the two types of stores:

stat <- rbind(ollies_out, wholefood_out)
stat %>%
  group_by(location_name) %>%
  summarise(medianExp = median(exp))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   location_name          medianExp
##   <chr>                      <dbl>
## 1 Ollie's Bargain Outlet      43.4
## 2 Whole Foods Market          85.6

So its clear that in Atlanta, Whole Foods Stores are typically located in neighbourhoods with a greater exposure to higher insert snazzy title, whereas Ollies Bargain Outlet is typically found in neighbourhoods with lower implications.

3.4 Implications

So what does all of this mean? What can such insights be used for?
